    <body><div type="letter">
      <p>Fordhook. Monday. 7th Decr.</p>
      <p>My Dearest. The Birdie is overflowing with happiness over an innundation of letters from its dearest mate. One by Fordhook post-- two from Ockham by George! I have only a few minutes now to spare, for I am going to Mrs Somerville at Chelsea this afternoon, and the Hen wishes me to</p>
      <p>set out in good time, that I may not be in the dark this foggy day when I return.-- I am as happpy here as I could possibly be without ou, &amp; the dear old Hen pets the Bird very much.--</p>
      <p>Mr Wharton was here yesterday, &amp; is decidely of opinion that the price of corn will rise, &amp; rents in consequence, after Christmas. It has already risen in France.-- I asked him to come to</p>
      <p>Ockham, but you must give him a specific invitation.--</p>
      <p>The Hen has asked a few people to dinner on Thursday to meet us-- Dr Lushington, Mr Grieg, the Murrays &amp;c. I must end. I am very well.--</p>
      <p>Your most affecte Birdie A.A.K.</p>
    </div></body>
